          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">What Is a Hire Purchase?</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A hire purchase (sometimes called a commercial hire purchase or CHP) is a business finance arrangement where the finance company purchases the asset on your behalf and hires it to you over an agreed term. You have full use of the asset from day one, make regular instalments (plus interest), and ownership transfers to you once all payments — including any residual or balloon — are made.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Hire purchase is one of the core business finance structures in Australia, alongside chattel mortgage and finance lease. It is available exclusively to ABN holders and is designed for assets used primarily for business purposes. The structure has been a staple of Australian commercial lending for decades and is well understood by accountants, lenders, and the ATO.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The key distinction from a chattel mortgage is the GST treatment. With a hire purchase, you do not own the asset during the term (the finance company does), so GST is included in each instalment and claimed progressively in each BAS period. With a chattel mortgage, you own the asset immediately and claim all GST upfront. This difference makes hire purchase attractive for businesses that prefer not to manage a large upfront GST credit.</p>
        </section>

